                                "mergeField": "%3Cdiv%3E%3Cspan%20style=%22font-size:%2012pt;%22%3E%3Cstrong%3EGuidance%20for%20Disclosure%203-1%3C/strong%3E%3C/span%3E%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3EThis%20disclosure%20requires%20information%20on%20how%20the%20organization%20has%20determined%20its%20material%20topics.%20The%20list%20of%20material%20topics%20is%20reported%20under%20Disclosure%203-2%20in%20this%20Standard.%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3EThe%20organization%20is%20required%20to%20use%20the%20applicable%20GRI%20Sector%20Standards%20when%20determining%20its%20material%20topics.%20If%20any%20of%20the%20topics%20that%20are%20included%20in%20the%20applicable%20Sector%20Standards%20have%20been%20determined%20by%20the%20organization%20as%20not%20material,%20the%20organization%20is%20required%20to%20list%20them%20in%20the%20GRI%20content%20index%20and%20explain%20why%20they%20are%20not%20material.%20See%20Requirement%205%20and%20Requirement%207%20in%20GRI%201:%20Foundation%202021%20and%20Box%205%20in%20this%20Standard%20for%20more%20information.%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3EIn%20the%20absence%20of%20applicable%20Sector%20Standards,%20the%20organization%20should%20explain%20how%20it%20has%20considered%20impacts%20commonly%20associated%20with%20its%20sectors,%20and%20whether%20any%20of%20these%20impacts%20have%20been%20determined%20as%20not%20material,%20together%20with%20an%20explanation%20for%20why%20this%20is%20the%20case.%20The%20organization%20should%20also%20explain%20how%20it%20has%20considered%20impacts%20commonly%20associated%20with%20its%20products%20and%20geographic%20locations.%20See%20section%201%20in%20this%20Standard%20and%20the%20Sector%20Standards%20for%20guidance%20on%20impacts%20commonly%20associated%20with%20sectors,%20products,%20and%20geographic%20locations.%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3E&nbsp;%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3E%3Cstrong%3EGuidance%20to%203-1-a-i%3C/strong%3E%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3EThe%20organization%20should%20describe%20the%20methods%20used%20to%20identify%20its%20impacts,%20for%20example,%20economic,%20environmental,%20social,%20and%20human%20rights%20impact%20assessments,%20grievance%20mechanisms,%20or%20using%20information%20from%20external%20sources,%20such%20as%20civil%20society%20organizations.%20The%20organization%20should%20describe%20the%20sources%20and%20the%20evidence%20it%20has%20used%20to%20identify%20the%20impacts.%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3EThe%20organization%20should%20also%20describe%20the%20scope%20it%20has%20defined%20when%20identifying%20the%20impacts,%20for%20example,%20whether%20it%20has%20identified%20short-term%20as%20well%20as%20long-term%20impacts.%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3EThe%20organization%20should%20also%20describe%20any%20limitations%20or%20exclusions,%20for%20example,%20whether%20it%20has%20excluded%20business%20relationships%20from%20certain%20parts%20of%20its%20value%20chain%20when%20identifying%20the%20impacts.%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3EDisclosure%202-12%20in%20GRI%202:%20General%20Disclosures%202021%20requires%20information%20on%20the%20role%20of%20the%20highest%20governance%20body%20in%20overseeing%20the%20organization&rsquo;s%20due%20diligence%20and%20other%20processes%20to%20identify%20its%20impacts%20on%20the%20economy,%20environment,%20and%20people.%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3E&nbsp;%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3E%3Cstrong%3EGuidance%20to%203-1-a-ii%3C/strong%3E%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3EThe%20organization%20should%20describe%20how%20it%20has%20assessed%20the%20significance%20of%20the%20impacts,%20including%20any%20assumptions%20and%20subjective%20judgments%20it%20has%20made.The%20significance%20of%20an%20actual%20negative%20impact%20is%20determined%20by%20the%20severity%20of%20the%20impact%20(scale,%20scope,%20and%20irremediable%20character),%20while%20the%20significance%20of%20a%20potential%20negative%20impact%20is%20determined%20by%20the%20severity%20and%20likelihood%20of%20the%20impact.%20In%20the%20case%20of%20potential%20negative%20human%20rights%20impacts,%20the%20severity%20of%20the%20impact%20takes%20precedence%20over%20its%20likelihood.%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3EThe%20significance%20of%20an%20actual%20positive%20impact%20is%20determined%20by%20the%20scale%20and%20scope%20of%20the%20impact,%20while%20the%20significance%20of%20a%20potential%20positive%20impact%20is%20determined%20by%20its%20scale%20and%20scope%20as%20well%20as%20its%20likelihood.%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3ESee%20section%201%20in%20this%20Standard%20for%20more%20guidance%20on%20assessing%20the%20significance%20of%20impacts.%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3EThe%20organization%20should%20explain%20if%20it%20has%20used%20a%20different%20approach%20to%20prioritize%20its%20impacts,%20for%20example,%20if%20it%20has%20prioritized%20potential%20negative%20environmental%20impacts%20based%20on%20severity%20only.%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3EThe%20organization%20should%20also%20describe%20how%20it%20has%20defined%20the%20threshold%20to%20determine%20which%20topics%20are%20material%20for%20reporting,%20and%20whether%20it%20has%20tested%20its%20selection%20of%20material%20topics%20with%20potential%20information%20users%20and%20experts.%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3EThe%20organization%20is%20required%20to%20report%20whether%20the%20highest%20governance%20body%20is%20responsible%20for%20reviewing%20and%20approving%20the%20reported%20information,%20including%20the%20organization&rsquo;s%20material%20topics,%20under%20Disclosure%202-14%20in%20GRI%202.%20The%20organization%20should%20explain%20any%20changes%20to%20its%20initial%20selection%20of%20material%20topics%20following%20internal%20approval%20and%20testing%20with%20potential%20information%20users%20and%20experts.%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3EFor%20transparency,%20the%20organization%20can%20provide%20a%20visual%20representation%20of%20the%20prioritization%20that%20shows%20the%20initial%20list%20of%20topics%20it%20has%20identified%20and%20the%20threshold%20it%20has%20set%20for%20reporting.%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3E&nbsp;%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3E%3Cstrong%3EGuidance%20to%203-1-b%20%3C/strong%3E%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3ERequirement%203-1-b%20enables%20the%20organization%20to%20explain%20how%20engagement%20with%20stakeholders%20and%20experts%20informs%20the%20ongoing%20identification%20and%20assessment%20of%20its%20impacts.The%20organization%20can%20report%20whether%20and%20how%20it%20has%20prioritized%20stakeholders%20for%20engagement%20and%20the%20methods%20used%20to%20engage%20with%20them.%20It%20can%20also%20report%20any%20conflicting%20interests%20that%20have%20arisen%20among%20different%20stakeholders%20and%20how%20the%20organization%20has%20resolved%20these%20conflicting%20interests.%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3E&nbsp;%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3E%3Cspan%20style=%22font-size:%2012pt;%22%3E%3Cstrong%3EGuidance%20for%20Disclosure%203-2%3C/strong%3E%3C/span%3E%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3EThis%20disclosure%20requires%20information%20on%20the%20organization&rsquo;s%20material%20topics.%20The%20process%20of%20determining%20material%20topics%20is%20reported%20under%20Disclosure%203-1%20in%20this%20Standard.%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3EThe%20organization%20is%20required%20to%20include%20the%20material%20topics%20listed%20under%20this%20disclosure%20in%20the%20GRI%20content%20index.%20If%20the%20organization%20has%20determined%20any%20of%20the%20topics%20included%20in%20the%20applicable%20Sector%20Standards%20as%20not%20material,%20then%20the%20organization%20is%20required%20to%20list%20them%20in%20the%20content%20index%20and%20explain%20why%20they%20are%20not%20material.%20See%20Requirement%205%20and%20Requirement%207%20in%20GRI%201:%20Foundation%202021%20for%20more%20information.%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3E&nbsp;%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3E%3Cstrong%3EGuidance%20to%203-2-a%20%3C/strong%3E%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3EThe%20organization%20can%20group%20material%20topics%20by%20relevant%20categories%20if%20this%20helps%20communicate%20its%20impacts.%20For%20example,%20the%20organization%20can%20indicate%20which%20of%20its%20material%20topics%20represent%20its%20negative%20human%20rights%20impacts.%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3E&nbsp;%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3E%3Cstrong%3EGuidance%20to%203-2-b%3C/strong%3E%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3ERequirement%203-2-b%20enables%20the%20organization%20to%20explain%20why%20a%20topic%20that%20it%20determined%20as%20material%20in%20the%20previous%20reporting%20period%20is%20no%20longer%20considered%20to%20be%20material%20or%20why%20a%20new%20topic%20has%20been%20determined%20as%20material%20for%20the%20current%20reporting%20period.%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3E&nbsp;%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3E%3Cspan%20style=%22font-size:%2012pt;%22%3E%3Cstrong%3EGuidance%20for%20Disclosure%203-3%3C/strong%3E%3C/span%3E%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3EThis%20disclosure%20requires%20the%20organization%20to%20explain%20how%20it%20manages%20each%20of%20its%20material%20topics.%20This%20means%20that%20the%20organization%20is%20required%20to%20report%20this%20disclosure%20for%20each%20of%20its%20material%20topics.%20The%20requirements%20in%20this%20disclosure%20apply%20to%20every%20material%20topic.%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3EIn%20addition%20to%20this%20disclosure,%20there%20may%20also%20be%20disclosures%20and%20guidance%20in%20the%20Topic%20Standards%20and%20Sector%20Standards%20that%20address%20reporting%20information%20about%20how%20the%20organization%20manages%20a%20topic.%20For%20example,%20some%20Topic%20Standards%20contain%20disclosures%20about%20specific%20actions%20or%20methods%20to%20manage%20a%20topic.%20The%20organization%20does%20not%20need%20to%20repeat%20this%20information%20under%20Disclosure%203-3%20if%20it%20is%20already%20reported%20under%20another%20disclosure.%20The%20organization%20can%20report%20the%20information%20once%20and%20provide%20a%20reference%20to%20this%20information%20to%20fulfill%20the%20corresponding%20requirements%20in%20Disclosure%203-3.%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3EIf%20the%20organization&rsquo;s%20approach%20to%20managing%20a%20material%20topic,%20such%20as%20its%20policies%20or%20actions%20taken,%20applies%20to%20other%20material%20topics,%20the%20organization%20does%20not%20need%20to%20repeat%20this%20information%20for%20each%20topic.%20The%20organization%20can%20report%20this%20information%20once,%20with%20a%20clear%20explanation%20of%20all%20the%20topics%20it%20covers.%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3EIf%20the%20organization%20cannot%20report%20the%20required%20information%20about%20an%20item%20specified%20in%20this%20disclosure%20because%20the%20item%20(e.g.,%20policy,%20action)%20does%20not%20exist,%20it%20can%20comply%20with%20the%20requirement%20by%20reporting%20this%20to%20be%20the%20case.%20The%20organization%20can%20explain%20the%20reasons%20for%20not%20having%20this%20item%20or%20describe%20any%20plans%20to%20develop%20it.%20The%20disclosure%20does%20not%20require%20the%20organization%20to%20implement%20the%20item%20(e.g.,%20developing%20a%20policy),%20but%20to%20report%20that%20the%20item%20does%20not%20exist.%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3EIf%20the%20organization%20does%20not%20manage%20a%20material%20topic,%20it%20can%20comply%20with%20the%20requirements%20under%20this%20disclosure%20by%20explaining%20the%20reasons%20for%20not%20managing%20the%20topic%20or%20describing%20any%20plans%20to%20manage%20it.%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3E&nbsp;%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3E%3Cstrong%3EGuidance%20to%203-3-a%20%3C/strong%3E%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3ERequirement%203-3-a%20enables%20the%20organization%20to%20indicate%20if%20a%20topic%20is%20material%20because%20of%20negative%20impacts,%20positive%20impacts,%20or%20both.%20It%20does%20not%20require%20a%20list%20of%20all%20the%20impacts%20identified%20or%20a%20detailed%20description%20of%20the%20impacts.%20Instead,%20the%20organization%20can%20provide%20a%20high-level%20overview%20of%20the%20impacts%20it%20has%20identified.%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3E&nbsp;%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3EDescribing%20negative%20impacts%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3EThe%20organization%20can%20describe:%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3E&bull;%20Whether%20the%20negative%20impacts%20are%20actual%20or%20potential;%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3E&bull;%20The%20time%20frame%20of%20the%20negative%20impacts%20(i.e.,%20whether%20the%20negative%20effects%20are%20short-term%20or%20long-term%20and%20when%20they%20are%20likely%20to%20arise);%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3E&bull;%20Whether%20the%20negative%20impacts%20are%20systemic%20(e.g.,%20child%20labor%20or%20forced%20labor%20in%20countries%20where%20the%20organization%20operates%20or%20sources%20materials%20from)%20or%20are%20related%20to%20individual%20incidents%20(e.g.,%20an%20oil%20spill)%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3E&bull;%20The%20economic%20resources,%20environmental%20resources,%20and%20stakeholders%20(without%20identifying%20specific%20individuals)%20that%20are%20negatively%20affected%20or%20could%20be%20negatively%20affected,%20including%20their%20geographic%20location.%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3EReporting%20information%20about%20negative%20impacts%20can%20help%20the%20organization%20demonstrate%20that%20it%20recognizes%20these%20impacts%20and%20has%20taken%20action%20or%20intends%20to%20address%20them.%20The%20organization%20may%20have%20concerns%20about%20reporting%20information%20about%20negative%20impacts%20even%20if%20these%20impacts%20are%20publicly%20known.%20In%20cases%20where%20negative%20impacts%20are%20publicly%20known,%20failure%20to%20acknowledge%20these%20impacts%20and%20to%20explain%20how%20they%20are%20being%20addressed%20could%20have%20consequences%20for%20the%20organization%20financially,%20operationally,%20or%20reputationally.%20If%20the%20organization%20is%20unable%20to%20disclose%20specific%20information%20(e.g.,%20because%20of%20stakeholders&rsquo;%20right%20to%20privacy),%20it%20can%20provide%20the%20information%20in%20aggregated%20or%20anonymized%20form,%20or%20it%20can%20make%20a%20reference%20to%20the%20impacts%20commonly%20associated%20with%20its%20sectors,%20its%20products,%20or%20geographic%20locations.%20%5B11%5D%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3E&nbsp;%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3EDescribing%20positive%20impacts%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3EThe%20organization%20can%20describe:%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3E&bull;%20Whether%20the%20positive%20impacts%20are%20actual%20or%20potential%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3E&bull;%20The%20time%20frame%20of%20the%20positive%20impacts%20(i.e.,%20whether%20the%20positive%20effects%20are%20short-term%20or%20long-term%20and%20when%20they%20are%20likely%20to%20arise)%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3E&bull;%20The%20activities%20that%20result%20in%20the%20positive%20impacts%20(e.g.,%20products,%20services,%20investments,%20procurement%20practices)%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3E&bull;%20The%20economic%20resources,%20environmental%20resources,%20and%20stakeholders%20(without%20identifying%20specific%20individuals)%20that%20are%20positively%20affected%20or%20could%20be%20positively%20affected,%20including%20their%20geographic%20location.%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3E&nbsp;%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3E%3Cstrong%3EGuidance%20to%203-3-b%20%3C/strong%3E%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3EThe%20way%20the%20organization%20is%20involved%20with%20negative%20impacts%20determines%20how%20it%20should%20address%20the%20impacts%20and%20whether%20it%20has%20a%20responsibility%20to%20provide%20for%20or%20cooperate%20in%20their%20remediation%20(see%20section%202.3%20in%20GRI%201:%20Foundation%202021).%20Requirement%203-3-b%20provides%20contextual%20information%20that%20aids%20an%20understanding%20of%20the%20actions%20taken%20by%20the%20organization%20to%20manage%20its%20negative%20impacts.%20The%20actions%20taken%20are%20reported%20under%203-3-d-i%20and%203-3-d-ii.%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3EUnder%20requirement%203-3-b,%20the%20organization%20is%20required%20to%20report%20whether%20it%20is%20involved%20with%20the%20negative%20impacts%20through%20its%20activities%20or%20as%20a%20result%20of%20its%20business%20relationships.%20Where%20possible,%20the%20organization%20should%20also%20report:%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3E&bull;%20Whether%20it%20is%20or%20could%20be%20causing%20or%20contributing%20to%20the%20negative%20impacts%20through%20its%20activities;%20or%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3E&bull;%20Whether%20the%20impacts%20are%20or%20could%20be%20directly%20linked%20to%20its%20operations,%20products,%20or%20services%20by%20its%20business%20relationships%20even%20if%20it%20has%20not%20contributed%20to%20them.%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3ESee%20Box%203%20in%20this%20Standard%20for%20more%20information%20on%20causing,%20contributing,%20or%20being%20directly%20linked%20to%20negative%20impacts.%20Under%20requirement%203-3-b,%20the%20organization%20is%20also%20required%20to%20describe%20the%20activities%20or%20business%20relationships.%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3EThis%20enables%20the%20organization%20to%20indicate%20if%20the%20impacts%20related%20to%20a%20material%20topic%20are%20widespread%20in%20the%20organization&rsquo;s%20activities%20or%20business%20relationships,%20or%20if%20the%20impacts%20concern%20specific%20activities%20or%20business%20relationships.%20If%20the%20impacts%20concern%20specific%20activities,%20the%20organization%20should%20describe%20the%20types%20of%20activities%20(e.g.,%20manufacturing,%20retail)%20and%20their%20geographic%20location.%20If%20the%20impacts%20concern%20specific%20business%20relationships,%20the%20organization%20should%20describe%20the%20types%20of%20business%20relationships%20(e.g.,%20suppliers%20of%20raw%20materials,%20franchisees),%20their%20position%20in%20the%20value%20chain,%20and%20their%20geographic%20location.%20For%20example,%20if%20the%20organization%20has%20identified%20that%20its%20activities%20at%20specific%20sites%20could%20cause%20water%20pollution,%20it%20should%20describe%20the%20types%20of%20activities%20carried%20out%20at%20these%20sites%20and%20the%20geographic%20location%20of%20these%20sites.%20Or,%20if%20the%20organization%20has%20identified%20that%20it%20is%20directly%20linked%20to%20child%20labor%20by%20the%20business%20relationships%20in%20its%20supply%20chain,%20it%20should%20specify%20the%20types%20of%20suppliers%20using%20child%20labor%20(e.g.,%20sub-contractors%20doing%20embroidery%20work%20for%20the%20organization&rsquo;s%20products)%20and%20the%20geographic%20location%20of%20these%20suppliers.%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3EThe%20organization%20can%20provide%20additional%20contextual%20information%20for%20understanding%20the%20extent%20of%20its%20impacts.%20Adding%20to%20the%20previous%20examples,%20the%20organization%20can%20report%20how%20many%20of%20its%20sites%20could%20cause%20water%20pollution%20(e.g.,%2060%25%20of%20sites,%20five%20out%20of%2012%20sites)%20or%20the%20proportion%20of%20production%20these%20sites%20represent,%20or%20it%20can%20report%20the%20estimated%20number%20of%20sub-contractors%20using%20child%20labor%20that%20do%20embroidery%20work%20for%20the%20organization.%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3E&nbsp;%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3E%3Cstrong%3EGuidance%20to%203-3-c%20%3C/strong%3E%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3ERequirement%203-3-c%20entails%20describing%20the%20policies%20or%20commitments%20the%20organization%20has%20developed%20specifically%20for%20the%20topic,%20in%20addition%20to%20the%20policy%20commitments%20reported%20under%20Disclosure%202-23%20in%20GRI%202:%20General%20Disclosures%202021.%20If%20the%20organization%20has%20described%20its%20policies%20for%20a%20material%20topic%20under%20Disclosure%202-23,%20it%20can%20provide%20a%20reference%20to%20this%20information%20under%203-3-c%20and%20does%20not%20need%20to%20repeat%20the%20information.%20See%20Disclosure%202-23%20in%20GRI%202%20for%20guidance%20on%20how%20to%20report%20information%20about%20policies.%20When%20reporting%20its%20commitments%20regarding%20the%20material%20topic,%20the%20organization%20should%20provide%20a%20statement%20of%20intent%20to%20manage%20the%20topic%20or%20explain:%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3E&bull;%20The%20organization&rsquo;s%20stance%20on%20the%20topic%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3E&bull;%20Whether%20the%20commitment%20to%20manage%20the%20topic%20is%20based%20on%20regulatory%20compliance%20or%20extends%20beyond%20it%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3E&bull;%20Compliance%20with%20authoritative%20intergovernmental%20instruments%20related%20to%20the%20topic.%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3E&nbsp;%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3E%3Cstrong%3EGuidance%20to%203-3-d%20%3C/strong%3E%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3ERequirement%203-3-d%20enables%20the%20organization%20to%20explain%20how%20it%20responds%20to%20its%20impacts.%20It%20does%20not%20require%20a%20detailed%20description%20of%20actions%20taken%20in%20relation%20to%20each%20impact.%20Instead,%20the%20organization%20can%20provide%20a%20high-level%20overview%20of%20how%20it%20manages%20its%20impacts.%20The%20organization%20should%20report%20how%20it%20integrates%20the%20findings%20from%20its%20identification%20and%20assessment%20of%20impacts%20across%20relevant%20internal%20functions%20and%20processes,%20including:%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3E&bull;%20The%20level%20and%20function%20within%20the%20organization%20that%20has%20been%20assigned%20responsibility%20for%20managing%20the%20impacts%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3E&bull;%20The%20internal%20decision-making,%20budget%20allocation,%20and%20oversight%20processes%20(e.g.,%20internal%20audit)%20to%20enable%20effective%20actions%20to%20manage%20the%20impacts.%20Disclosure%202-12%20and%20Disclosure%202-13%20in%20GRI%202%20require%20information%20on%20the%20role%20of%20the%20highest%20governance%20body%20in%20overseeing%20the%20management%20of%20the%20organization&rsquo;s%20impacts%20and%20on%20how%20it%20delegates%20responsibility%20for%20this.%20The%20organization%20should%20also%20report%20how%20it%20manages%20actual%20impacts%20identified%20in%20previous%20reporting%20periods%20and%20which%20it%20continues%20to%20manage%20during%20the%20current%20reporting%20period.%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3E&nbsp;%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3E%3Cstrong%3EGuidance%20to%203-3-d-i%20%3C/strong%3E%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3EThe%20organization%20should%20report:%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3E&bull;%20Examples%20of%20actions%20taken%20to%20prevent%20or%20mitigate%20potential%20negative%20impacts%20(e.g.,%20adaptation/modification%20measures,%20facility%20upgrading,%20training,%20red-flag%20systems)%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3E&bull;%20Approaches%20taken%20to%20prevent%20or%20mitigate%20systemic%20negative%20impacts%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3E&bull;%20How%20the%20organization%20applies%20the%20precautionary%20principle,%20including:%20-how%20the%20organization%20proactively%20informs%20the%20public%20about%20potential%20negative%20impacts%20of%20its%20activities,%20products,%20and%20services,%20and%20how%20it%20deals%20with%20related%20questions%20and%20complaints%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3E-%20The%20organization&rsquo;s%20support%20or%20contribution%20to%20scientific%20research%20related%20to%20evaluating%20potential%20negative%20impacts%20of%20its%20activities,%20products,%20and%20services%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3E-The%20organization&rsquo;s%20participation%20in%20collaborative%20efforts%20to%20share%20knowledge%20and%20to%20prevent%20negative%20impacts%20of%20its%20activities,%20products,%20and%20services%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3E&bull;%20How%20the%20organization%20uses%20or%20increases%20its%20leverage%20to%20motivate%20its%20business%20relationships%20to%20prevent%20or%20mitigate%20potential%20negative%20impacts.%20For%20example,%20whether%20the%20organization%20uses%20or%20increases%20its%20leverage%20by%20enforcing%20contractual%20requirements,%20implements%20incentives%20such%20as%20future%20orders,%20provides%20training%20and%20support,%20or%20actively%20collaborates%20with%20other%20actors%20to%20motivate%20its%20business%20relationships%20to%20prevent%20or%20mitigate%20potential%20negative%20impacts%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3E&bull;%20Whether%20the%20organization%20has%20terminated%20a%20business%20relationship%20because%20it%20lacks%20the%20leverage%20to%20prevent%20or%20mitigate%20potential%20negative%20impacts%20and,%20if%20so,%20whether%20it%20has%20assessed%20if%20terminating%20the%20relationship%20could%20itself%20result%20in%20negative%20impacts.%20See%20Guidance%20to%202-23-a-iii%20in%20GRI%202%20for%20more%20information%20on%20&lsquo;precautionary%20principle&rsquo;.%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3E&nbsp;%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3E%3Cstrong%3E%20Guidance%20to%203-3-d-ii%20%3C/strong%3E%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3EThe%20organization%20should%20report:%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3E&bull;%20examples%20of%20actions%20taken%20to%20remediate%20actual%20negative%20impacts,%20including%20examples%20of%20specific%20remedies%20or%20types%20of%20remedy%20provided%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3E&bull;%20How%20grievance%20mechanisms%20or%20other%20remediation%20processes%20(reported%20under%20Disclosure%202-25%20in%20GRI%202)%20have%20made%20it%20possible%20for%20actual%20negative%20impacts%20to%20be%20remediated.%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3ESee%20Disclosure%202-25%20in%20GRI%202%20for%20more%20information%20on%20processes%20to%20remediate%20negative%20impacts.%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3E&nbsp;%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3E%3Cstrong%3E%20Guidance%20to%203-3-e%20%3C/strong%3E%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3ERequirement%203-3-e%20enables%20the%20organization%20to%20report%20information%20about%20the%20effectiveness%20of%20its%20actions%20to%20manage%20its%20impacts.%20Tracking%20the%20effectiveness%20of%20its%20actions%20is%20necessary%20for%20an%20organization%20to%20learn%20if%20its%20policies%20and%20processes%20are%20being%20implemented%20optimally.%20It%20is%20also%20necessary%20for%20knowing%20if%20it%20has%20responded%20effectively%20to%20its%20impacts%20and%20to%20drive%20continuous%20improvement.%20The%20organization%20should%20also%20report%20information%20about%20the%20effectiveness%20of%20its%20actions%20to%20manage%20actual%20impacts%20from%20previous%20reporting%20periods.%20This%20applies%20in%20cases%20where%20the%20organization%20has%20assessed%20the%20effectiveness%20of%20these%20actions%20or%20derived%20lessons%20during%20the%20current%20reporting%20period.%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3E&nbsp;%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3E%3Cstrong%3E%20Guidance%20to%203-3-e-i%20%3C/strong%3E%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3EProcesses%20used%20to%20track%20the%20effectiveness%20of%20actions%20can%20include%20internal%20or%20external%20auditing%20or%20verification,%20impact%20assessments,%20measurement%20systems,%20stakeholder%20feedback,%20grievance%20mechanisms,%20external%20performance%20ratings,%20and%20benchmarking.%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3E&nbsp;%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3E%3Cstrong%3EGuidance%20to%203-3-e-ii%20%3C/strong%3E%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3EWhen%20reporting%20on%20goals%20and%20targets,%20the%20organization%20should%20report:%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3E&bull;%20How%20the%20goals%20and%20targets%20are%20set%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3E&bull;%20Whether%20and%20how%20the%20goals%20and%20targets%20take%20into%20account%20the%20sustainability%20context%20in%20which%20the%20impacts%20take%20place%20(e.g.,%20sustainable%20development%20goals%20and%20conditions,%20the%20limits%20and%20demands%20placed%20on%20environmental%20resources).%20See%20the%20Sustainability%20context%20principle%20in%20GRI%201%20for%20more%20information%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3E&bull;%20Whether%20the%20goals%20and%20targets%20are%20informed%20by%20expectations%20in%20authoritative%20intergovernmental%20instruments%20and,%20where%20relevant,%20by%20scientific%20consensus%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3E&bull;%20whether%20goals%20and%20targets%20are%20mandatory%20(based%20on%20legislation)%20or%20voluntary.%20If%20they%20are%20mandatory,%20the%20organization%20can%20list%20the%20relevant%20legislation%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3E&bull;%20The%20organization&rsquo;s%20activities%20or%20business%20relationships%20to%20which%20the%20goals%20and%20targets%20apply;%20&bull;%20the%20baseline%20for%20the%20goals%20and%20targets%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3E&bull;%20The%20timeline%20for%20achieving%20the%20goals%20and%20targets.%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3E&nbsp;Targets%20can%20be%20qualitative%20(e.g.,%20implementing%20a%20management%20system%20by%20a%20certain%20date)%20or%20quantitative%20(e.g.,%20reducing%20greenhouse%20gas%20%5BGHG%5D%20emissions%20by%20a%20certain%20percentage%20by%20a%20certain%20date).%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3EThe%20indicators%20used%20to%20evaluate%20progress%20can%20also%20be%20qualitative%20or%20quantitative.%20Quantitative%20indicators%20can%20bring%20precision%20and%20enable%20comparisons.%20Qualitative%20information%20is%20often%20needed%20to%20put%20quantitative%20information%20into%20context,%20enable%20its%20interpretation,%20and%20determine%20which%20comparisons%20and%20conclusions%20are%20likely%20to%20be%20most%20valid.%20The%20Topic%20Standards%20and%20Sector%20Standards%20include%20qualitative%20and%20quantitative%20indicators.%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3E&nbsp;%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3E%3Cstrong%3EGuidance%20to%203-3-e-iii%20%3C/strong%3E%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3ERequirement%203-3-e-iii%20enables%20the%20organization%20to%20show%20the%20extent%20to%20which%20the%20actions%20taken%20have%20been%20effective.%20Information%20on%20the%20effectiveness%20of%20the%20actions%20can%20be%20obtained,%20for%20example,%20from%20the%20outcomes%20of%20internal%20or%20external%20auditing%20or%20verification,%20data%20collected%20through%20measurement%20systems,%20and%20stakeholder%20feedback.%20The%20organization%20should%20show%20that%20there%20is%20a%20credible%20link%20between%20the%20specific%20action%20taken%20by%20the%20organization%20and%20the%20effective%20management%20of%20impacts.%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3EFor%20example,%20to%20show%20the%20effectiveness%20of%20its%20actions%20to%20support%20its%20suppliers%20with%20improving%20their%20working%20conditions,%20the%20organization%20can%20report%20survey%20feedback%20from%20the%20suppliers&rsquo;%20workers%20showing%20that%20working%20conditions%20have%20improved.%20Additional%20information%20the%20organization%20can%20provide%20includes%20data%20showing%20a%20decrease%20in%20the%20number%20of%20incidents%20identified%20through%20independent%20audits.%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3ESimilarly,%20to%20demonstrate%20the%20effectiveness%20of%20its%20actions%20to%20improve%20the%20quality%20of%20its%20water%20discharge,%20the%20organization%20can%20report%20data%20showing%20a%20decrease%20in%20the%20concentration%20of%20total%20dissolved%20solids%20(mg/L)%20in%20the%20water%20discharge.When%20reporting%20progress%20toward%20its%20goals%20and%20targets,%20the%20organization%20should%20report%20whether%20progress%20is%20satisfactory%20or%20not.%20If%20a%20goal%20or%20target%20has%20not%20been%20achieved,%20the%20organization%20should%20explain%20why.%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3E&nbsp;%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3E%3Cstrong%3EGuidance%20to%203-3-e-iv%20%3C/strong%3E%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3EManaging%20impacts%20is%20typically%20an%20ongoing%20process%20requiring%20continuous%20improvement%20based%20on%20learning%20from%20practice.%20The%20organization%20is%20not%20required%20to%20provide%20a%20detailed%20description%20of%20lessons%20learned%20in%20relation%20to%20each%20material%20topic.%20Instead,%20the%20organization%20can%20provide%20examples%20to%20show%20how%20it%20incorporates%20lessons%20learned%20to%20manage%20impacts%20more%20successfully%20in%20the%20future.%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3EFor%20example,%20the%20organization%20can%20briefly%20describe%20lessons%20learned%20that%20have%20led%20to%20changes%20in%20its%20policies%20or%20practices%20(e.g.,%20training%20for%20workers,%20giving%20additional%20attention%20to%20the%20performance%20of%20suppliers),%20or%20that%20have%20led%20to%20plans%20for%20changes%20that%20will%20manage%20impacts%20more%20successfully%20in%20the%20future.%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3ELessons%20learned%20may%20be%20derived%20from%20the%20organization&rsquo;s%20own%20processes%20(e.g.,%20root%20cause%20analysis),%20from%20its%20business%20relationships,%20or%20from%20stakeholder%20or%20expert%20feedback.%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3E&nbsp;%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3E%3Cstrong%3EGuidance%20to%203-3-f%20%3C/strong%3E%3C/div%3E%0A%3Cdiv%3EThe%20organization%20can%20explain,%20for%20example,%20whether%20and%20how%20affected%20stakeholders%20have%20been%20involved%20in%20determining%20an%20appropriate%20remedy%20for%20a%20negative%20impact%20or%20how%20stakeholder%20feedback%20is%20used%20to%20assess%20the%20effectiveness%20of%20the%20actions%20taken.%3C/div%3E",
